description:
Mark presents Jesus as a dynamic man of power. Everything in Mark happens quickly and dramatically. Mark has no time for things like family trees and stories about Jesusâ€™ birth. His story about Jesus begins like thisâ€¦

The beginning of the good news 
about Jesus the Messiah, the Son of God,
as it is written in Isaiah the prophet:
â€œI will send my messenger ahead of you,
who will prepare your wayâ€”
â€œa voice of one calling in the wilderness,
â€˜Prepare the way for the Lord,
make straight paths for him.â€™â€
â€“ Mark 1:1â€“3

The first thing Mark tells us is who the gospel is about. Itâ€™s the good news about Jesus. Mark then leads straight into a quotation from the prophet Isaiah, which refers to a messenger who would prepare the way for Jesus. Usually, royalty would send a servant ahead of them to announce their coming and to prepare the road ahead. Thatâ€™s what Mark is talking about.

He also tells us, right up front, the identity of the one who is coming. Mark quotes from Isaiah 40, which was well known to the Jews of that day. They knew that it was talking about coming of the One who was the Lord God Himself.

The Gospel of Mark starts with a messenger. Without a messenger there can be no good news. In this Gospel, the first one to speak is the messenger who prepares people to meet Jesus. This presents you with a challenge. Are you willing to be a messenger for Jesus? Think of someone you know who needs to know Jesus. Make a plan to introduce them to the Lord.
